### How to Fork a Repo, Pull Latest Content, Complete Activities, and Share with the Instructor

Follow the step-by-step instructions below to fork a repository, pull the latest content, complete the activities, and share your work with the instructor.

#### Step 1: Fork the Repository

1. Navigate to the training GitHub Repositort [HERE](https://github.com/mimikgit/Awesome-edgeEngine-training)
2. Click the "Fork" button in the top-right corner of the page.
3. Select your GitHub account to create the fork.

#### Step 2: Clone the Forked Repository

1. Click the "Code" button in your forked repository.
2. Copy the URL provided.
3. Open your command-line interface (CLI) or terminal.
4. Navigate to the directory where you want to clone the repository.
5. Run the following command: `git clone [URL]`, replacing `[URL]` with the copied URL.

#### Step 3: Pull the Latest Content

1. Navigate to the cloned repository directory in your CLI or terminal.
2. Run the following command to fetch the latest updates from the original repository: `git pull upstream master`.

#### Step 4: Complete the Activities

1. Open the repository files in your preferred code editor.
2. Complete the activities as instructed in the README or activity files.
3. Save your changes.

#### Step 5: Commit and Push Your Changes

1. Navigate to the repository directory in your CLI or terminal.
2. Run the following command to stage your changes: `git add .`.
3. Run the following command to commit your changes: `git commit -m "Completed activities"`.
4. Run the following command to push your changes to your forked repository: `git push origin master`.

#### Step 6: Share the Repo Link with the Instructor

1. Copy the URL of your forked repository from GitHub.
2. Open the Slack channel.
3. Paste the URL and add a message to the instructor, such as "Here's the link to my repository: [URL]."
4. Press "Enter" to send the message.

#### NOTE
Please keep your repository up to date with your local content by pushing the updates. 
---

If you encounter any issues or have questions, please reach out to the instructor. 

